doc.ContractDescription: OXIDATION STATE OF LUNAR GLASSES: IMPLICATIONS FOR SURFACE AND ERUPTIVE PROCESSES ON THE MOON REPORTS OF FE3 IN LUNAR MATERIALS, BOTH GLASSES AND MINERALS, EXTEND BACK TO THE TIME OF THE MISSIONS THEMSELVES [E.G., 1]. THE LUNAR INTERIOR FO2 HOWEVER, IS IW 1, A REGION WHERE SIGNIFICANT FE3 IS NOT EXPECTED TO BE PRESENT. HOWEVER, RECENT STUDIES INDICATE THE MOON IS NOT AS DRY AS PREVIOUSLY THOUGHT [E.G., 2]. THIS FRESH INSIGHT RE-OPENS THE QUESTION OF THE PRESENCE OF FE3 IN LUNAR GLASSES, WHICH MAY WELL BE RELATED TO THE OXIDIZING POTENTIAL OF THE NEWLY RECOGNIZED LUNAR H2O. PRELIMINARY RESULTS ON A SMALL SAMPLING OF LUNAR GLASS BEADS INDICATE THEY CONTAIN 0 25% FE3 [3]. ALTHOUGH MANY SAMPLES APPEAR HOMOGENEOUS, SEVERAL BEADS DISPLAY FE3 ZONING PROFILES CONSISTENT WITH A LATESTAGE OXIDATION EVENT. THE PRESENCE OF FE3 IS SIGNIFICANT BECAUSE IT RECORDS OXYGEN POTENTIAL AND THUS TRACES THE EVOLUTION OF OXYGEN THROUGH THE PARAMETER OF OXYGEN FUGACITY (FO2) IN SOLAR SYSTEM MATERIALS. QUANTIFYING FO2 IN IGNEOUS MELTS IS IMPORTANT BOTH FOR CONSTRAINING PLANETARY INTERIOR PHYSICAL CONDITIONS, BUT ALSO FOR INVESTIGATING POTENTIAL CHANGES DURING DEVOLATILIZATION DRIVEN ERUPTIVE MECHANISMS. HISTORICALLY, QUANTIFICATION OF FE3 IN GLASSES REQUIRED EITHER WET CHEMISTRY OR MOSSBAUER SPECTROSCOPY, TECHNIQUES THAT REQUIRE LARGE SAMPLE SIZES AND ARE PERFORMED ON BULK MATERIAL. HOWEVER, OUR GROUP HAS DEVELOPED A NEW SYNCHROTRON X RAY ABSORPTION SPECTROSCOPY (XAS) CALIBRATION THAT ALLOWS MEASUREMENT OF FE3 AT MICROSCALES IN SITU, THEREBY RESOLVING POTENTIAL VARIATIONS WITHIN SAMPLES IN THIN SECTIONS. THE NEW GLASS CALIBRATION [4,5] SPANS 120 DIFFERENT SILICATE AND REDOX COMPOSITIONS, AND PERMITS ACCURATE IN SITU MICROSCALE FE3 MEASUREMENTS WITH AN AVERAGE ERROR OF 2.9 %, SIMILAR TO THAT OF MOSSBAUER. USING THIS NEW CALIBRATION, THE CENTRAL OBJECTIVE OF THIS PROPOSAL IS TO DETERMINE THE RANGE OF IRON OXIDATION STATES PRESENT IN LUNAR GLASSES, BOTH THOSE THAT FORMED IN THE LUNAR INTERIOR THROUGH IGNEOUS MEANS AND THOSE THAT FORMED ON THE SURFACE DURING IMPACT. TO ACHIEVE OUR GOALS, WE WILL COMPLETE THE FOLLOWING TASKS: 1) DETERMINE THE FE3 FE RATIO OF A SUITE OF LUNAR GLASSES, INCLUDING LUNAR GLASS BEADS, MARE BASALT GLASS FRAGMENTS, AND AGGLUTINATE GLASSES, AND IDENTIFY ANY INTER OR INTRASAMPLE VARIATIONS AND THEIR POTENTIAL ORIGINS; 2) USE EXPERIMENTALLY DETERMINED OXIDATION RATES TO QUANTIFY COOLING TIMES OF THE LUNAR GLASS BEADS NECESSARY TO RESULT IN OBSERVED FE3 ZONATION; USE THE COOLING TIMES TO CONSTRAIN FIRE FOUNTAIN PROCESSES; 3) EVALUATE THE POTENTIAL FE3 OF AGGLUTINATE GLASSES TO CONSTRAIN OXIDATION REDUCTION CONDITIONS GENERATED DURING IMPACT AND THE ROLE OF BOTH IMPACTOR AND SURFACE VOLATILES. THIS WORK IS HIGHLY RELEVANT TO NASAS SOLAR SYSTEM WORKINGS PROGRAM SPECIFICALLY THE GOALS TO STUDY VOLCANISM (INVESTIGATE HOW VOLCANIC ACTIVITY CAN PROVIDE INSIGHT INTO INTERIOR PROCESSES) AND EVOLUTION AND MODIFICATION OF SURFACES (CHARACTERIZE FLUID INVENTORIES THAT INTERACT WITH THE SURFACE). REFERENCES: [1] DYAR&CONSOLMAGNO (1982) LPS XIII 193 194. [2] SAAL ET AL. (2008) NATURE 454, 192 196. [3] MCCANTA ET AL. (2015) LPS XXXXVI. [4] DYAR&MCCANTA (2014) AGU FALL MTG. A4858. [5] MCCANTA ET AL. (2015) LPS XXXXVI.

doc.ContractDescription: THIS PROPOSAL SEEKS TO DEVELOP NEARLY COMPREHENSIVE INVENTORIES OF MICROORGANISMS PRESENT IN SAMPLES FROM NASA'S CLEAN ROOM SPACE VEHICLE ASSEMBLY ROOMS AND ON SPACECRAFT SURFACES. IT ADDRESSES RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE NATIONAL RESEARCH COUNCIL THAT NASA SHOULD REQUIRE THE ROUTINE COLLECTION OF PHYLOGENETIC DATA TO A STATISTICALLY APPROPRIATE LEVEL TO ENSURE THAT THE MICROBIAL DIVERSITY OF ASSEMBLY, TEST, AND LAUNCH OPERATIONS (ATLO) ENVIRONMENTS, AND OF ALL OF NASA SPACECRAFT TO BE SENT TO MARS AND IT RESPONDS TO THE ROSES-2009 RESEARCH ANNOUNCEMENT PLANETARY PROTECTION RESEARCH SOLICITATION: NNH09ZDAOOIN-PPR: THE DEVELOPMENT OR ADAPTATION OF MODERN MOLECULAR ANALYTICAL METHODS TO RAPIDLY DETECT, CLASSIFY, AND/OR ENUMERATE THE WIDEST POSSIBLE SPECTRUM OF EARTH MICROBES CARRIED BY SPACECRAFT (ON SURFACES AND/OR IN BULK MATERIALS, ESPECIALLY AT LOW DENSITIES) BEFORE, DURING, AND AFTER ASSEMBLY AND LAUNCH PROCESSING. OF PARTICULAR INTEREST ARE METHODS CAPABLE OF IDENTIFYING MICROBES WITH HIGH POTENTIAL FOR SURVIVING SPACECRAFT FLIGHT OR PLANETARY ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS (E.G., ANAEROBES, PSYCHROPHILES, RADIATION-RESISTANT ORGANISMS). WE WILL DEVELOP AND VALIDATE NEW TITANIUM CHEMISTRY PROTOCOLS FOR THE ROCHE GENOME SEQUENCER FLX PLATFORM THAT CAN EFFICIENTLY SEQUENCE 400 BP PYROTAGS AMPLIFIED FROM RAPIDLY EVOLVING REGIONS IN 16S RIBOSOMAL RNA GENES. EACH PYROTAG WILL SERVE AS A PROXY FOR THE OCCURRENCE OF A MICROBIAL GENOME IN ARCHIVED AND NEW SAMPLES FROM NASAS CLEAN ROOM ASSEMBLY AND SPACECRAFT SURFACES. THROUGH BIOINFORMATICS ALGORITHMS THAT COMPARE PYROTAGS TO MOLECULAR DATABASES WE WILL GENERATE AN INVENTORY OF MICROBIAL TAXA IN THE SAMPLES. WE WILL ALSO USE THE NEW GENERATION-3 PHYLCHIPS UNDER DEVELOPMENT AT THE LAWRENCE BERKELEY NATIONAL LABORATORIES TO GENERATE CONFIRMATORY AND COMPLEMENTARY TAXONOMIC INVENTORIES. AS PART OF THIS EFFORT, WE WILL DEVELOP A MERGED DATABASE THAT RESOLVES THE TAXONOMY EMPLOYED BY PYROTAG AND PHYLOCHIP ANALYSES. TAXONOMIC INVENTORIES AFFORDED BY PYROTAGS AND PHYLOCHIPS CAN IDENTIFY THE LIKELY PRESENCE OF MICROBES FROM EXTREMOPHYLLIC LINEAGES INCLUDING RADIATION OR DESICCANT RESISTANT MICROBES, EXTREME PSYCHROPHILES, OR HEAT RESISTANT ORGANISMS THAT HAVE A GREATER PROBABILITY OF GROWTH IN THE EXTREME ENVIRONMENTS OF OTHER SOLAR SYSTEM OBJECTS. WE WILL USE THE SAME PYROTAG DATA TO IDENTIFY THE NUMBER OF DIFFERENT KINDS OF MICROBES IN THE SAMPLES AND THEIR RELATIVE ABUNDANCE. KNOWLEDGE ABOUT THE DIVERSITY OF "HITCHHIKING" MICROBIAL COMMUNITIES CAN SET RELATIVE BOUNDS ON THE PROBABILITY THAT A COMMUNITY MEMBER WILL BE CAPABLE OF GROWTH IN AN EXTRATERRESTRIAL ENVIRONMENT; HIGH DIVERSITY COMMUNITIES ARE MORE LIKELY THAN SIMPLE COMMUNITIES TO CONTAIN MICROBES CAPABLE OF GROWTH IN EXTRATERRESTRIAL ENVIRONMENTS.
